text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!Absence of common consonants: Comparing English and Kaingang%0a%0a:Author: wtsin%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aConsonants in English that are missing in Kaingang%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe absence of common consonants revolves around the different categories of consonants that are missing from certain languages, and how the patterns are related to where these languages originate from. For example, as noted in the WALS (1), out of the languages which have no fricatives, most originate from parts of Australia. Additionally, the absence of fricatives is much more concentrated in one specific area than nasals or bilabials.%0a%0aPirahã is a language originating from South America, more specifically around parts of central/eastern Brazil. Its consonants differ from English in that it has no nasals (m, n, ŋ, etc).%0a%0aWhat I find interesting about the difference is that Pirahã doesn't only lack nasal consonants, but based on the inventory (3), it's also missing most of the consonants from the IPA chart. This raises the question, does the lack of sounds limit Pirahã's understandability/effectiveness in verbal communication, or the number of different words it can have? If not, is it because speakers are able to create and tell the subtle difference between sounds in different contexts, or maybe that words in Pirahã can take on more meanings than in English?%0a%0aSources%0a1) https://wals.info/chapter/18%0a2) https://wals.info/valuesets/18A-kng%0a3) https://phoible.org/inventories/view/477#tipa%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: C:)%0a(:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts:)%0a(:Title: Absence of common consonants: Comparing English and Kaingang:)
